{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774371022,"nonce":"yfCQvH8JXRnNi1OkhYjwfFYMIUk=","title":"Principled choice of evaluation perturbation amplitude for robustness testing","message":"## Problem\n\nWhen evaluating model robustness under perturbation, the perturbation amplitude must be:\n- Large enough that non-robust models show significant lateral deviation\n- Small enough that robust models can still reach the target\n- Not so large that ALL models fail\n- Not so small that differences are undetectable\n\nCurrently we pick amplitudes ad hoc (e.g., pert_scale=0.5). A principled method would make results more comparable across studies and model configurations.\n\n## Preliminary observations\n\nAt pert_scale=0.5 with our point mass (m=1, damping=10, workspace ±1m, reach 0.5m):\n- Robust models (APT lr=0.001): lat_dev ≈ 0.007\n- Standard models: lat_dev ≈ 0.013  \n- Low control cost: lat_dev ≈ 0.10\n\nThe effect is detectable but small. Higher perturbation might reveal more.\n\n## Possible approaches\n\n1. Binary search: find amplitude where baseline model has X% endpoint error increase (e.g., 50%)\n2. Robustness curve: evaluate at many amplitudes, plot performance vs amplitude\n3. Theory-based: derive from plant dynamics (damping, mass) and control cost\n4. Match to human experiments: use same perturbation-to-force ratio as Crevecoeur \u0026 Scott\n\n## Status\n\nNeeds investigation. An Opus analysis of the optimization approach is pending.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}